class Logger
{
    private readonly ITimeStampFormatter _timeStampFormatter;

    public Logger(ITimeStampFormatter timeStampFormatter)
    {
        _timeStampFormatter = timeStampFormatter;
    }

    public void Log(string message)
    {
        string formattedMessage = $"[{_timeStampFormatter.Format()}] {message}";
        Console.WriteLine(formattedMessage);
    }
}

interface ITimeStampFormatter
{
    string Format();
}

class CorrectTimestampFormatter : ITimeStampFormatter
{
    public string Format() => $"[{DateTime.Now:yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss}]";
}
```
The `Logger` class now only logs messages, and the timestamp formatting is delegated to an interface (`ITimeStampFormatter`). This follows SRP by separating concerns into separate classes.
3. The explanation of the refactoring is that the original code violates SRP because it handles both logging and timestamp formatting. By moving the timestamp formatting logic to a separate class, we remove this responsibility from `Logger`, following SRP.

